SpaceX Falcon 9 first stage Landing Prediction¶

Executive Summary:¶

Background:¶

Technical: Obtaining and integrating data from APIs and webscraping are essential skills for data professionals. As such, this project is the result of practice using APIs (SpaceX API) and webscraping (bs4) to obtain and compare private and public datasets for greater: model result insights, dataset insights and better final recommendations. Model interpretation used Shapley (aka SHAP) values to measure the model's feature importances and their degree of impact on predictions, especially useful in this case as a Random Forest Classifier yielded the best result on validation data.

Business: Since its first successful landing in 2014, SpaceX has achieved a success rate of over 80%. Having a data team that could understand and gather the key factors that influence landing success is crucial their ongoing success. This project's analysis uses various machine learning classification techniques to identify the most significant features impacting booster landing outcomes, drawing from historical launch data including parameters such as payload mass, launch site, orbital target, and booster configuration.

Findings:¶

The class balances within the datasets were acceptable with Webscrape data containing 29.75% landing failures and API containing 33.33% landing failures.

According to the initial correlation analysis, as design revisions were made over time, the factors of flight number, date, and block increased as they are all incremental data. Similarly, blocks weren't the only incremental design improvements as grid fins and landing legs were introduced. Post-2015 Hardware configurations tended to include grid fins (small titanium wings that provide steering capacity) and landing legs (telescoping carbon fiber appendages to stabilize upon touchdown). Their consistent usage was highly correlated to landing success. For the rocket itself, reused rockets and the latest block "Block 5" were consistently strong indicators of success. All of these factors were positively correleated with landing outcomes.

For launch sites, most early launches occured at "CCSFS", resulting in a negative correlation with success (-0.18). Both datasets' correlations were positive toward "KSC" as a launch site.

Payload mass of less than 8000 kg tended to be the most problematic overall especially for lower orbit (esp. LEO, ISS, PO). Both datasets show that lower weights struggled in a way that heavier payloads did not.

API suggested higher `orbit` (GTO, SO) continued to suffer failures (-0.21,-0.15 correlation respectively), whereas lower orbits (esp. SSO 0.17, VLEO 0.17) except ISS tended towards success. However, only the webscrape data indicated that the "HEO" and "LEO" `orbit` had positive correlations (0.05,0.12) with negative for GTO matching the API (-0.17).

Model Analysis:

The Random Forest model had the best scores, though other popular classification models were considered: decision trees, logistic regressors, SVCs and XGBoost Classifiers. Recall score was selected to evaluate model predictions due to the high cost of a false negative. While false positives have costs in terms of operational expenses, these are significantly lower than the cost of an unexpected crash. In the end, the random forest model produced the highest recall and f1-score (API: 0.833, Webscrape: 0.923)

Recommendations:¶

No matter which dataset the model was trained on, the results favored hardware configurations with the Block 5 booster that included legs and grid fins.
Payload mass should attempt to stay above 6100~kg; this mass was shown to be highly failure-prone, accounting for 75% of failures in both datasets.

Conclusions:¶

Recent hardware revisions by Space X have paid off, especially since the introduction of the Block 5. While managing payload mass and higher orbits, such as GTO continue to be a source of difficulty. SpaceX boosting landings have continued to improve, no matter which source of data one chooses.

def getBoosterVersion(data):
    for x in data['rocket']:
       if x:
        response = requests.get("https://api.spacexdata.com/v4/rockets/"+str(x)).json()
        BoosterVersion.append(response['name'])
In [4]:
# Takes the dataset and uses the launchpad column to call the API and append the data to the list
def getLaunchSite(data):
    for x in data['launchpad']:
       if x:
         response = requests.get("https://api.spacexdata.com/v4/launchpads/"+str(x)).json()
         Longitude.append(response['longitude'])
         Latitude.append(response['latitude'])
         LaunchSite.append(response['name'])
In [5]:
# Takes the dataset and uses the payloads column to call the API and append the data to the lists
def getPayloadData(data):
    for load in data['payloads']:
       if load:
        response = requests.get("https://api.spacexdata.com/v4/payloads/"+load).json()
        PayloadMass.append(response['mass_kg'])
        Orbit.append(response['orbit'])
In [6]:
# Takes the dataset and uses the cores column to call the API and append the data to the lists
def getCoreData(data):
    for core in data['cores']:
            if core['core'] != None:
                response = requests.get("https://api.spacexdata.com/v4/cores/"+core['core']).json()
                Block.append(response['block'])
                ReusedCount.append(response['reuse_count'])
                Serial.append(response['serial'])
            else:
                Block.append(None)
                ReusedCount.append(None)
                Serial.append(None)
            Outcome.append(str(core['landing_success'])+' '+str(core['landing_type']))
            Flights.append(core['flight'])
            GridFins.append(core['gridfins'])
            Reused.append(core['reused'])
            Legs.append(core['legs'])
            LandingPad.append(core['landpad'])

# A function to Extract years from the date 
def extract_year(df):
    year=[]
    for i in df["Date"]:
        year.append(i.split("-")[0])
    return year

Helper Functions: Webscrape¶

In [8]:
def date_time(table_cells):
    """
    This function returns the data and time from the HTML  table cell
    Input: the  element of a table data cell extracts extra row
    """
    return [data_time.strip() for data_time in list(table_cells.strings)][0:2]

def booster_version(table_cells):
    """
    This function returns the booster version from the HTML  table cell 
    Input: the  element of a table data cell extracts extra row
    """
    out=''.join([booster_version for i,booster_version in enumerate( table_cells.strings) if i%2==0][0:-1])
    return out

def landing_status(table_cells):
    """
    This function returns the landing status from the HTML table cell 
    Input: the  element of a table data cell extracts extra row
    """
    out=[i for i in table_cells.strings][0]
    if "Success" in out or "Controlled" in out:
        out = 1
    else:
        out = 0
    return out


def get_mass(table_cells):
    mass=unicodedata.normalize("NFKD", table_cells.text).strip()
    if mass:
        mass.find("kg")
        new_mass=re.sub(r"\D","",mass[0:mass.find("kg")+2])
        if len(new_mass)>5:
            new_mass=new_mass[-4:]
        elif not new_mass:
            new_mass = 0
    
    else:
        new_mass=0
    return new_mass


def extract_column_from_header(row):
    """
    This function returns the landing status from the HTML table cell 
    Input: the  element of a table data cell extracts extra row
    """
    if (row.br):
        row.br.extract()
    if row.a:
        row.a.extract()
    if row.sup:
        row.sup.extract()
        
    colunm_name = ' '.join(row.contents)
    
    # Filter the digit and empty names
    if not(colunm_name.strip().isdigit()):
        colunm_name = colunm_name.strip()
        return colunm_name

Helper Function Confusion Matrix Display

In [9]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(y,y_predict,model_name):
    """
    Plots  a confusion matrix, given a model and predictions.
    """
    cm = confusion_matrix(y, y_predict)
    ax= plt.subplot()
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, ax = ax)
    ax.set_xlabel('Predicted labels')
    ax.set_ylabel('True labels')
    ax.set_title(f'Confusion Matrix {model_name}')
    ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['did not land', 'landed']) 
    ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['did not land', 'landed'])
    plt.savefig(f"cm_{model_name}.png", bbox_inches="tight")
    plt.show()

#get launch data from API or load
if os.path.exists("df_webscrape.json"):
    df_clean = pd.read_json("df_webscrape.json")
else:

    response = requests.get("https://api.spacexdata.com/v4/launches/past")
    #check request success
    print(response.status_code)
    #static request url
    static_json_url='https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.cloud-object-storage.appdomain.cloud/IBM-DS0321EN-SkillsNetwork/datasets/API_call_spacex_api.json'
    #make DF from json
    data = pd.json_normalize(response.json())

    # Lets take a subset of our dataframe keeping only the features we want and the flight number, and date_utc.
    data = data[['rocket', 'payloads', 'launchpad', 'cores', 'flight_number', 'date_utc']]

    # We will remove rows with multiple cores because those are falcon rockets with 2 extra rocket boosters and rows that have multiple payloads in a single rocket.
    data = data[data['cores'].map(len)==1]
    data = data[data['payloads'].map(len)==1]

    # Since payloads and cores are lists of size 1 we will also extract the single value in the list and replace the feature.
    data['cores'] = data['cores'].map(lambda x : x[0])
    data['payloads'] = data['payloads'].map(lambda x : x[0])

    # We also want to convert the date_utc to a datetime datatype and then extracting the date leaving the time
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date_utc']).dt.date

    # Using the date we will restrict the dates of the launches
    data = data[data['date'] <= datetime.date(2020, 11, 13)]
    data.to_json("raw_data_via_api.json")
    
    # Call getBoosterVersion
    getBoosterVersion(data)
    # Call getLaunchSite
    getLaunchSite(data)
    # Call getPayloadData
    getPayloadData(data)
    # Call getCoreData
    getCoreData(data)
    # Construct dataset
    launch_dict = {
        'FlightNumber': list(data['flight_number']),
        'Date': list(data['date']),
        'BoosterVersion':BoosterVersion,
        'PayloadMass':PayloadMass,
        'Orbit':Orbit,
        'LaunchSite':LaunchSite,
        'Outcome':Outcome,
        'Flights':Flights,
        'GridFins':GridFins,
        'Reused':Reused,
        'Legs':Legs,
        'LandingPad':LandingPad,
        'Block':Block,
        'ReusedCount':ReusedCount,
        'Serial':Serial,
        'Longitude': Longitude,
        'Latitude': Latitude
    }
    df_clean = pd.DataFrame(launch_dict)
    df_clean.to_json("df_webscrape.json")

Make dataset or load¶

In [12]:
if os.path.exists('spacex_web_scraped.csv'):
    df_webscrape = pd.read_csv('spacex_web_scraped.csv')
else:
    # brew URL soup
    static_url = "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_Falcon_9_and_Falcon_Heavy_launches&oldid=1027686922"
    request = requests.get(static_url)
    soup =  BeautifulSoup(request.content)
    # Extract columns, var_names
    html_tables = list(soup.find_all("table"))
    # get column names
    column_names = []
    for i in html_tables[2].find_all("th"):
        name = extract_column_from_header(i)
        if name is not None and len(str(name)) > 0:
            column_names.append(name)
    # create dict
    launch_dict= {col:[] for col in column_names if "Date" not in col}
    # Added some new columns
    launch_dict['Version Booster']=[]
    launch_dict['Booster landing']=[]
    launch_dict['Date']=[]
    launch_dict['Time']=[]

    extracted_row = 0
    #Extract each table 
    for table_number,table in enumerate(soup.find_all('table',"wikitable plainrowheaders collapsible")):
    # get table row 
        for rows in table.find_all("tr"):
            #check to see if first table heading is as number corresponding to launch a number 
            if rows.th:
                if rows.th.string:
                    flight_number=rows.th.string.strip()
                    flag=flight_number.isdigit()
            else:
                flag=False
            #get table element 
            row=rows.find_all('td')
            #if it is number save cells in a dictonary 
            if flag:
                extracted_row += 1
                # Flight Number value
                launch_dict["Flight No."].append(flight_number)
                datatimelist=date_time(row[0])
                # Date value
                date = datatimelist[0].strip(',')
                launch_dict["Date"].append(date)
                # Time value
                time = datatimelist[1]
                launch_dict["Time"].append(time)
                # Booster version
                bv=booster_version(row[1])
                if not(bv):
                    bv=row[1].a.string
                # truncate booster name
                bv = re.sub(r"(F9 )(([A-Z]+[0-9]?)|v1\.[0-9])(.+)?",r"\2",bv)
                launch_dict['Version Booster'].append(bv)
                # Launch Site
                launch_site = row[2].a.string
                if launch_site=="Cape Canaveral" or launch_site=="CCAFS":
                    launch_site = "CCSFS"
                launch_dict['Launch site'].append(launch_site)
                # Payload
                payload = row[3].a.string
                launch_dict['Payload'].append(payload)
                # Payload Mass
                payload_mass = get_mass(row[4])
                launch_dict['Payload mass'].append(payload_mass)
                # Orbit
                orbit = row[5].a.string
                if "Polar" in orbit:
                    orbit = "LEO"
                launch_dict['Orbit'].append(orbit)
                # Customer
                if row[6].a != None:
                    customer = row[6].a.string
                    launch_dict['Customer'].append(customer)
                else: 
                    launch_dict['Customer'].append("Unknown")
                # Launch outcome
                launch_outcome_raw = list(row[7].strings)[0]
                launch_outcome = 0 if launch_outcome_raw == "Failure" else 1
                launch_dict['Launch outcome'].append(launch_outcome)
                # Booster landing
                booster_landing = landing_status(row[8])
                launch_dict['Booster landing'].append(booster_landing)      

    df_webscrape = pd.DataFrame(launch_dict)
    # Export to CSV
    df_webscrape.to_csv('spacex_web_scraped.csv', index=False)

Guide to Launch Orbits, via Wikipedia¶

  • LEO: Low Earth orbit (LEO)is an Earth-centred orbit with an altitude of 2,000 km (1,200 mi) or less (approximately one-third of the radius of Earth),[1] or with at least 11.25 periods per day (an orbital period of 128 minutes or less) and an eccentricity less than 0.25.[2] Most of the manmade objects in outer space are in LEO [1].

  • VLEO: Very Low Earth Orbits (VLEO) can be defined as the orbits with a mean altitude below 450 km. Operating in these orbits can provide a number of benefits to Earth observation spacecraft as the spacecraft operates closer to the observation[2].

  • GTO A geosynchronous orbit is a high Earth orbit that allows satellites to match Earth's rotation. Located at 22,236 miles (35,786 kilometers) above Earth's equator, this position is a valuable spot for monitoring weather, communications and surveillance. Because the satellite orbits at the same speed that the Earth is turning, the satellite seems to stay in place over a single longitude, though it may drift north to south,” NASA wrote on its Earth Observatory website [3] .

  • SSO (or SO): It is a Sun-synchronous orbit also called a heliosynchronous orbit is a nearly polar orbit around a planet, in which the satellite passes over any given point of the planet's surface at the same local mean solar time [4] .

  • ES-L1 :At the Lagrange points the gravitational forces of the two large bodies cancel out in such a way that a small object placed in orbit there is in equilibrium relative to the center of mass of the large bodies. L1 is one such point between the sun and the earth [5].

  • HEO A highly elliptical orbit, is an elliptic orbit with high eccentricity, usually referring to one around Earth [6].

  • ISS A modular space station (habitable artificial satellite) in low Earth orbit. It is a multinational collaborative project between five participating space agencies: NASA (United States), Roscosmos (Russia), JAXA (Japan), ESA (Europe), and CSA (Canada) [7]

  • MEO Geocentric orbits ranging in altitude from 2,000 km (1,200 mi) to just below geosynchronous orbit at 35,786 kilometers (22,236 mi). Also known as an intermediate circular orbit. These are "most commonly at 20,200 kilometers (12,600 mi), or 20,650 kilometers (12,830 mi), with an orbital period of 12 hours [8]

  • HEO Geocentric orbits above the altitude of geosynchronous orbit (35,786 km or 22,236 mi) [9]

  • GEO It is a circular geosynchronous orbit 35,786 kilometres (22,236 miles) above Earth's equator and following the direction of Earth's rotation [10]

  • PO It is one type of satellites in which a satellite passes above or nearly above both poles of the body being orbited (usually a planet such as the Earth [11]

def add_val_annot(df:pd.DataFrame,col):
    for ind,tick in enumerate(geocentric_orbit_order):
        # get score from df
        score = df.loc[df["Orbit"] == tick, col].values[0]
        plt.annotate(f" {score:.1%}",((float(score),ind+.1)))
orbz = df.groupby("Orbit",as_index=False)["Class"].mean()
sns.barplot(data=orbz,y="Orbit",x="Class",orient="h",order=geocentric_orbit_order)
add_val_annot(orbz,"Class")
plt.title("Launch Success Rate by Orbit:\n Lower Orbits Show Difficulty")
plt.ylabel("Orbit (by distance from Earth desc.)")
plt.xlabel("Percent of Launches Successful")
plt.xlim(-0.01,1.15)
plt.show()

Train Models¶

Train/Save Helper

In [39]:
def train_model(model,model_name,X_train,Y_train):
    model_path = f"{model_name}.pkl"
    if os.path.exists(model_path):
        with open(model_path,"rb") as file:
            model= pickle.load(file)
        return model
    else:
        model.fit(X_train,Y_train)
        with open(model_path,"wb") as file:
            pickle.dump(model,file)
        return model
In [40]:
# train decision tree
tree_cv = train_model(tree_cv,"DecisionTree",X_train,Y_train)
In [41]:

In [42]:

Eval Helper Function¶

In [44]:
def eval_model(model:GridSearchCV,model_name,X_test,Y_test,score_df=scores):
    print("best hyperparameters:",model.best_params_)
    score= model.score(X_test,Y_test)
    results = {"model":[model_name],f"{refit} score":[score]}
    print(f"best {refit} score: {score:.1%}")
    score_df = pd.concat([score_df,pd.DataFrame(results)],ignore_index=True)
    y_hat = model.predict(X_test)
    plot_confusion_matrix(Y_test,y_hat,model_name)
    return score_df
